<h1>LG Washer tE Error Code — Fix It Same Day</h1>

<p>tE on an LG washer means a temperature sensor is reading out of range — the control can't trust the water or heater temperature, so it stops the cycle. It shows up most on models with an internal heater or steam, and it's usually the temperature sensor (thermistor) or the heating circuit. Here's what it means and what we check. Same-day across LA, Orange County and Ventura. Call (323) 990-7550.</p>

<h2>What the tE Code Means</h2>
<p>tE is a temperature fault. LG washers with heated or steam cycles read water and heater temperature through a thermistor — a sensor whose resistance changes with heat. When the value coming back falls outside the range the control expects, it can't safely manage the heater, so it stops and flags tE. It's a feedback problem: the machine isn't sure how hot things are, so it won't keep heating blind.</p>

<h2>What Causes a tE Error on an LG Washer</h2>
<p>In order of how often we find it:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>A faulty temperature sensor (thermistor)</strong> reading out of range — the most common cause.</li>
  <li><strong>A failed heating element or its circuit</strong> on heated/steam models.</li>
  <li><strong>A loose connector or damaged wiring</strong> at the sensor.</li>
  <li><strong>A control-board fault</strong> — rare.</li>
</ul>

<h2>What You Can Safely Check First</h2>
<p>Try a power-cycle first — unplug the washer for a minute and restart it; a one-off glitch sometimes clears. After that, the thermistor and heater live inside the cabinet, so there's little safe DIY here. If tE returns, it needs a tech to test the sensor's resistance and check the heating circuit — guessing at internal electrical parts isn't worth the risk.</p>

<h2>When It's the Sensor or Heater (and What We Do)</h2>
<p>Our techs test the thermistor's resistance against spec and check the heater circuit for continuity to see which side is off. A drifting or open sensor gets replaced; a failed heater is a bigger job. Temperature sensor replacement runs $250–320 installed; heater-circuit work runs higher depending on the part. The $65 diagnostic is waived when we do the repair.</p>

<h2>tE vs Other LG Codes</h2>
<p>tE is about temperature — the heat sensor reading wrong. PE is about water level — the pressure sensor reading wrong. OE is a drain fault. If your washer only faults on hot or steam cycles, that fits tE; if it's drain or level trouble, look elsewhere.</p>

