<h2>Frequently Asked Questions — LG Washer tE Error</h2>

<h3>What does the tE code mean on my LG washer?</h3>
<p>tE means a temperature sensor is reading outside its normal range, so the control stops the cycle. It's most common on LG washers with an internal heater or steam, and it usually points to the sensor or heating circuit rather than the whole machine.</p>

<h3>Can I fix an LG washer tE error myself?</h3>
<p>Try a power-cycle first — unplug it for a minute and restart. The temperature sensor and heater are inside the cabinet, so if tE returns there's no safe DIY fix; a tech needs to test the thermistor and heating circuit.</p>

<h3>How much does it cost to fix an LG washer tE error?</h3>
<p>If it's the temperature sensor, replacement runs $250–320 installed; heater-circuit repairs run higher depending on the part. The $65 diagnostic is waived when we do the repair, and we test resistance before quoting. We're licensed with the Bureau of Household Goods and Services (#49573).</p>

<h3>Why does my LG washer show tE on a hot or steam cycle?</h3>
<p>Those cycles lean on the heater and its temperature sensor, so a drifting thermistor or a heater-circuit fault shows up exactly when heat is called for. The sensor reads a value the control rejects, and it stops with tE. We test the sensor and heater together to find which one is off.</p>

<h3>Is it safe to keep using my LG washer with a tE error?</h3>
<p>It's best to leave it off — the control stops the cycle because it can't verify temperature, and forcing it risks running the heater without proper feedback. A single power-cycle is fine to try, but a repeating tE needs a tech.</p>

